[normal]Introduction[bold]https://www.gov.uk/highway-code/introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The 
[normal]Introduction to the Highway Code[bold] includes: 
[normal]“
[normal]Although failure to comply with the other rules of The Highway Code will not, in itself, cause a person to be prosecuted, The Highway Code may be used in evidence in any court proceedings under the Traffic Acts (see 
[normal]The road user and the law
[normal]) to establish liability. This includes rules which use advisory wording such as ‘should/should not’ or ‘do/do not’.”
[normal] 
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/highway-code/introduction
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For c
[normal]yclists this can create a 
[normal]problem in that the Code uses the word ‘should’ when applied to advice on what to wear
[normal], Rule 59, see below
[normal]. 
[normal]For pedestrians the word ‘should’ is not use
[normal]d. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Advice for pedestrians states;
[normal]  (
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/rules-pedestrians-1-to-35
[normal] )
[normal]Rule 3
[normal]Help other road users to see you.[bold] Wear or carry something light-coloured, bright or fluorescent in poor daylight conditions. When it is dark, use reflective materials (e.g. armbands, sashes, waistcoats, jackets, footwear), which can be seen by drivers using headlights up to three times as
[normal] far away as non-reflective materials.” 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In practice compensati
[normal]on is sometimes reduced for
[normal] people cycling
[normal] due to not 
[normal]wear
[normal]ing
[normal] extra safety aids and pedestrians usually gain full compensation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To provide for fair compensation and support people’s right
[normal] to 
[normal]wear their normal clothing
[normal], the following changes are suggested. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Adding a
[normal] sentence to the ‘
[normal]Introduction[bold]’,
[normal]“However, liability should not be based on wearing extra safety aids in the case of pedestrians and cyclists.”
[normal] 
[normal]and revising Rule 59 as below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rule 59 [bold]https://www.gov.uk/rules-for-cyclists-59-to-82
[normal]Current version shown in
[normal] Italics
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clothing.
[normal] You should wear
[normal]and
[normal]r
[normal]ewording Rule 59,
[normal] c
[normal]ould provide
[normal] the framework
[normal] for social equality.
[normal]Clothing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The advice to wear a helmet was added to the Code in 1993 when evidence was still being collected and it was p
[normal]remature. In 2013 there is
[normal] evidence for a
[normal]nd against promotin
[normal]g their use, from both safety and social perspectives.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rule 163[bold] 
[normal]– suggested changes
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/using-the-road-159-to-203
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]‘pass vulnerable road users with extra care and generous clearance’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rule 213[bold] [bold]– [bold]suggested 
[normal]ch
[normal]a
[normal]n
[normal]ges
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/road-users-requiring-extra-care-204-to-225/motorcyclists-and-cyclists-211-to-213
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Take extra care passing cyclists, 
[normal]preferably leave 1.5m or more but at least a minimum passing distance of one metre between the motor vehicle and a bicyclist for speeds up to 30 mph. At higher speeds more space should be provided and sufficient to prevent contact with the person operating
[normal] the bicycle if the person were to fall into the driver’s lane of traffic. Pass with care and not at excessive speed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rule 2[bold]39[bold]Parking (239 to 247)
[normal] 
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/waiting-and-parki
[normal]ng/parking-239-to-247
[normal]includes
[normal];
[normal]‘
[normal]you 
[normal]MUST[bold] ensure you do not hit anyone when you open your door. Check for cyclists or other traffic
[normal]’ 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A separate rule rather
[normal] than including in ‘Parking’ wou
[normal]l
[normal]d
[normal] give more emphasis, ‘General rules section could be used.
[normal] 
[normal]People opening doors and causing accidents result in deaths and serious injury to cyclists
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]New 
[normal]Rule – suggested wording;
[normal]Opening doors [bold]safely[bold]A person 
[normal]MUST NOT[bold] cause a hazard to any person or vehicle by opening a door of a vehicle, leaving a door of a v
[normal]ehicle open, or getting off, or out of, a vehicle. Check for cyclists or other traffic
[normal]Maximum penalty— 6
[normal] penalty points
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Plus an enlarged picture illustrating the dangers of opening a car door could be provided
[normal]A link to 
[normal]rule 239 could be added.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Tailgating[bold] 
[normal]HGV type vehicles are required to leave at least a 2 seconds gap from the vehicle in front on all types of roads. 
[normal]Note, this allows for a better view on the inside area where cyclists are likely to be.
[normal]The above suggestions
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] 
[normal]the I
[normal]ntroductio
[normal]n, 
[normal]rules
[normal] 59, 163, 
[normal]213
[normal] and 239 plus 
[normal]new
[normal] Rule
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]could
[normal] resu
[normal]lt 
[normal]in 
[normal]fewer accidents
[normal].
[normal] 
