[normal]Part 2[bold]Design standards for cycling infrastructure [bold]The 
[normal]UK
[normal] provides
[normal] design
[normal] guidelines and 
[normal]DfT
[normal] issue guidance
[normal]. These do not generally result in high quality consistent standards for infrastructure and in some cases engineers will not provide cycling facilities at all or 
[normal]provide sub guidelines recommendations or not 
[normal]follow the
[normal] gui
[normal]delines.
[normal] 
[normal]A new
[normal] approach is needed based on
[normal] standards that form the minimum requirement for cycling 
[normal]infrastructure
[normal]. One standard already in use in Victoria, Australia, ‘
[normal]Design standards for bicycle facilities’
[normal], they provide 
[normal] 
[normal]'Cycle Notes',
[normal] a series of 
[normal]21 
[normal]in
[normal]formation bulletins on design standards for cycling infrastructure.
[normal]http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/Home/Moreinfoa
[normal]ndservices/Bicycles/StrategicDirectionsForCycling/BicycleFacilityDesignStandards.htm
[normal]The detail design 
[normal]of infrastructure for cycling is an important safety aspect
[normal] and guidelines are not adequate to meet the needs required.
[normal] The aim is for the ‘standards’ to direct the design engineers to what is required for best practice
[normal] and reduce their design time and costs
[normal]. The 
[normal]Netherlands
[normal] also provide high design standards and a 
[normal]UK
[normal] ‘Design standards’ would need to apply best practice
[normal] su
[normal]ch as CROW
[normal] when possible, for more information refer 
[normal]http://www.cycling-embassy.org.uk/wiki/dutch-cycle-infrastructure
[normal] 
[normal]. 
