[normal]Part 3[bold]General road safety improvements and consequ[bold]ences for cycling[bold]If Parliament passed a
[normal] 
[normal]Cycling 
[normal]Promotion and Road Safety Bill
[normal], (see 
[normal]Appendix 
[normal]A
[normal] for deta
[normal]ils)
[normal] 
[normal]this 
[normal]woul
[normal]d show that Parliament was
[normal] send
[normal]ing
[normal] a strong message
[normal] to improve safety for cycling
[normal]. In 
[normal]Wales
[normal] they 
[normal]had
[normal] a consultat
[normal]ion on cycling and 
[normal]this
[normal] may help to improve safety, see; 
[normal]http://wales.gov.uk/consultations/transport/activetravelbill/?lang=en
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Roads
[normal] in 
[normal]UK
[normal] cities have
[normal] developed over centuries and were not designed for large HGV type vehicles
[normal]. Delivery of goods to inner cities should be limited to 
[normal]using 
[normal]vehicles of about 2m wide and 8
[normal]m long as a general rule
[normal] 
[normal]for
[normal] a maximum
[normal] size
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]One e
[normal]xamples of 
[normal]a 
[normal]vehi
[normal]cles near to being s
[normal]uitable is
[normal] t
[normal]he 
[normal]MWB Hi-Roof Van at 1.9m wide and 5.7m long can carry 1300 kg.  
[normal]http://www.rabbitsvehiclehire.co.uk/vehicle/mwb-hi-roof-van/
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This would provide for more passing clearance for cyclists and reduce the risk when turning. 
[normal]It w
[normal]ould also benefit general traffic flow. 
[normal]If
[normal] some
[normal] larger vehicles 
[normal]gained permission
[normal] then
[normal] some restrictions on 
[normal]not 
[normal]delivering
[normal] during peak traffic
[normal] hours
[normal] could be r
[normal]equired
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
