[normal]Appendix A[bold]Proposed, Cycling Promotion and Road Safety Bill[bold]Aims -[bold]1 Promote a cycling consciousness that reflects in safer driver’s behavio
[normal]u
[normal]r. 
[normal]2 To reduce conflicts between all road users and improve road safety.
[normal]3 Develop quality cycling in
[normal]frastructure and junction designs/provisions.
[normal]4 Improve cycling networks across 
[normal]England
[normal] and 
[normal]Wales
[normal].
[normal]5 Create jobs and 
[normal]encourage 
[normal]extra visitors.
[normal]6 Increase the combined use of cycling and public transport.
[normal]7 Reduce traffic pollution by more people cycling an
[normal]d reduced speed limits.
[normal]8 Improve health by more people cycling more often.
[normal]9 Improve cycling safety by ‘Safety in Numbers’ 
[normal]Contents[bold]1[bold]Standard of cycling infrastructure[bold]1.1 A revised standard for cycling provisions and infrastructure shall be provided
[normal].
[normal]1.2
[normal] Cycling infrastructure and provisions shall be maintained and repaired so that they are safe and fit for purpose.
[normal]2[bold]Making the road environment more suitable for cycling[bold]To reduce cyclists feeling squeezed or threatened by motorised traffic, the foll
[normal]owing 
[normal]provisions shall be introduced;
[normal]2.1 No overtaking of cyclists shall be permitted at the 
[normal]pedestrian 
[normal]refuge or crossing or for a distance of 10m either side of the refuge or cros
[normal]sing.
[normal]2.2 Separate bypass cycle lane shall be provided at refuges if possi
[normal]ble
[normal].
[normal]3[bold]Passing clearance and speed restriction for motor vehicles passing cyclists.[bold]3.1 
[normal]Refer prop
[normal]osed Highway Code changes above.
[normal]3.2
[normal] On narrow roads, 5 m or less in width, the permitted maximum motor vehicle speed is 20 mph when passing
[normal] cyclists. 
[normal]4[bold]Ma[bold]ximum Speed limits[bold]4.1
[normal]To 
[normal]reduce deaths and serious injuries and 
[normal]improve road safety for all road users the following speed limits shall apply unless signed otherwise. 
[normal]Motorways
[normal] refer present Code
[normal]‘A’ roads dual carriageways 60 or 70 mph, depending on ri
[normal]sk level and if prov
[normal]ided with 
[normal]separate cycle paths.
[normal]‘A’ roads dual carriageways 60 mph, if not provided with separate cycle paths
[normal].
[normal]‘A’ roads single carriageways 60 mph, if provided with separate cycle paths
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]‘A’ roads single carriageways 50 mph, if not pr
[normal]ov
[normal]ided with separate cycle paths. 
[normal]Rural roads with centre lines and a minimum width of 6m
[normal] and good sight lines
[normal], 50 mph. 
[normal]Rural roads without centre lines 40 mph
[normal].
[normal]Urban roads 40 mph, 30 mph, 25 mph and 20 mph limits to suit the situation.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Notes
[normal]4A
[normal]The 25 
[normal]mph limit compared with the 30 mph roughly halves the fatality risk, see page
[normal]s
[normal] 12 Fig 4, 
[normal]13 Fig 5, (40 km/
[normal]hr
[normal] v 50km/
[normal]hr
[normal]).
[normal]http://www.monash.edu.au/miri/research/reports/muarc276.pdf
[normal] 
[normal]P
[normal]robability of death reduces f
[normal]rom about 0.65 at 30 mph (50 km/
[normal]hr
[normal]) to 0.3 at 25 mph (40 km/
[normal]hr
[normal]). 
[normal]http://www.who.int/violence_injury_prevention/p
[normal]ublications/road_traffic/world_report/speed_en.pdf
[normal]Many roads in urban areas are suited to 25 mph limits rather than 30 mph limits.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4B
[normal]The GB accident data for 2011 shows 979 deaths in non-built up areas compared with 816 for built up areas. Most 
[normal]deaths occurred on ‘A’ roads. For cycling ‘A’ roads pose a high risk and changes are needed urgently. The above suggestions could help lower the number killed and relate directly to the provision of cycling infrastructure.
[normal]5[bold]Junction layout and design[bold]5
[normal].1
[normal] Road
[normal] junctions need to be rated for risk to cyclists, starting with ‘A’ roads. Staggered junctions are often used by cyclists to cross major roads and many improvements are required.
[normal]6[bold]Funding of cycling infrastructure and general provision for cycling[bold]6
[normal].1 
[normal]Long term f
[normal]unding at a rate of £10 per person (index linked) or three perc
[normal]ent of the transport budget to
[normal] be provided 
[normal]for
[normal] cycling facil
[normal]ities. Short term e
[normal]xtra funding to assist
[normal].
[normal]7[bold]Lower drink drive limit[bold]7
[normal].1 To reduce the permitted blood alcohol level f
[normal]or drivers from 80 m
[normal]g per 100 ml of blood to 50 mg.
[normal]7
[normal].2 Zero blood alco
[normal]hol limits for young drivers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Note
[normal]7A
[normal]http://www.nice.org.uk/media/3FE/1A/Blo 
[normal]... Review.pdf
[normal]There is strong evidence that someone’s ability to drive is affected if they have any alcohol in their blood. Drivers with a BAC of between 0.02 and 0.05 have at least a three times greater risk of dying in a vehicle crash. This risk incr
[normal]eases to at least six times w
[normal]ith a BAC between 0.05 and 0.08.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7B
[normal]http://alcalc.oxfordjournals.org/conten ... 1.full.pdf
[normal] (USA report)
[normal]Studies show a 3 to 17 fold increas
[normal]ed risk of a fatal MVC with BAC &lt; 0.08 g/dl compared to sober drivers.(17 factor for 16-20 age group).
[normal]8[bold]Amended the arrangements for changing the clocks in the winter and summer.
[normal]refer
[normal]http://www.publications.parliament.uk/p ... 65/665.pdf
[normal] page 10.
[normal]The Department has strong evidence that more than
[normal]80 fewer people would be killed each year on 
[normal]Great Britain
[normal]’s roads if the Government
[normal]amended the arrang
[normal]ements for changing the clocks in the winter and summer.
[normal]Notes[bold] on costs;[bold]Congestion[bold]The Department for Transport's (
[normal]DfT's
[normal]) estimated that the cost of congestion to business is set to rise by £10-12 billion over the period from 2003 to 2025 (expressed in 2
[normal]002 prices). Adding in the value of the lost time experienced by other travellers raises this figure to £23-24 billion per annum.[2] 
[normal]Cutting congestion in towns and cities by more people cycling, assume 33% more, could result in more than £0.5 billion in
[normal] savings as a guide estimate.
[normal]http://www.publications.parliament.uk/p ... /87204.htm
[normal]Health[bold]“Take obesity: it already costs our NHS a staggering £4
[normal] billion a year. But within four years, that figure’s expected to rise to £6.3 billion
[normal].” David Cameron, 16 May 2011.
[normal]Obesity cost approximately £66 per person and expected to in
[normal]crease to about £100 per year.  
[normal]Potential savings by more cycling could be appr
[normal]oximately £1 b
[normal]illion per year. 
[normal]http://fullfact.org/factchecks/NHS_refo ... ealth-2732
[normal]Tourism[bold]Internationally, 1
[normal]2 % of Germans cycle to work, 27% Netherlands, 18% Denmark, 80+milion people in the USA have bicycles. The 
[normal]UK
[normal] cycling to work rate is about 1%-2% but in some cities is much higher. The 
[normal]UK
[normal] travel credit £19 billion compares with a debit of £32 billion. Loss
[normal] approximately, £13 billion per year, average approximately £200+ per person. Providing more and better cycling facilities and improved road safety measures would result in more visitors and more people cycling within the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. Potentially from a transfer of
[normal] 0.5% (1 in 200) in extra visitors to the UK and a reduced level of travellers overseas, a net benefit to the UK could be approxim
[normal]ately £255 million per year. 
[normal]Annual saving for 
[normal]UK
[normal], approximately £255 million per year.
[normal]Fuel [bold]and accident savings[bold]Many motor 
[normal]vehicle journeys are less than 3 miles and by more people cycling, savings could be made of p
[normal]otentially £1 billion per year. 
[normal]A depressingly high proportion of short trips are mad
[normal]e by car, 23% under a mile, 33% 
[normal]1 – 2 miles, and 79% 2 – 5 miles.
[normal] 
[normal]R
[normal]efer
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.sustrans.org.uk/assets/files ... s%2016.pdf
[normal] 
[normal] [bold]Reduced accidents to cyclists and all road users could potentially save £1 billion per year.
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.roadsafe.com/news/article.aspx?article=1317
[normal]Job creation[bold]http://www.bikeleagu
[normal]e.org/resources/rep ... _Dec20.pdf
[normal]The link provides estimates of 14 jobs per million dollar spent - about 20 per million pounds. Tourism jobs would add to these numbers. Estimating at 25 jobs per million pounds and £10 per person would result in 15000 
[normal]extra jobs being created. 
[normal]Summary of costs[bold]Potential savings 
[normal]from a ‘
[normal]Cycling Promotion and Road Safety Bill
[normal]’ 
[normal]could be more than £3 billion per year compared with an estimated cost of £0.6 billion per year. Over a 10 year period a net return of £24 billio
[normal]n appears possible.
